	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Calls for new EU-based dairy product auction market</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 February 2014
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The Irish Minister for Agriculture has questioned the growing dominance of the New Zealand-based ‘GlobalDairyTrade’ auction, run by Fonterra, and has called for the establishment of an EU dairy auction floor “to help the bloc’s dairy industry hedge risks after the abolition of quotas in April [2015]”. The Irish dairy sector is poised to increase milk production once EU production quotas have been abolished.</p><p>According to the commodities website <i>Agrimoney.com</i>, “the Eurex exchange already offers futures in butter, skim milk powder and whey, settled against cash, on values derived from France, Germany and the Netherlands.”</p><p>Some EU dairy companies actively participate in the GlobalDairyTrade auction: in December 2013, Arla announced that it would be “selling British skimmed milk powder [SMP] on Fonterra's fortnightly Global Dairy Trade”, starting from 17 December 2013.</p><p>According to the German-based dairy industry equipment supplier GEA, “increasing Asian demand for dairy products, in particular milk powder, is driving manufacturers to invest in the expansion of their production capacity.” GEA considers this to be the continuation of a trend “that really began in the last couple of years”. The company named “Dutch dairy giant FrieslandCampina” as its most significant contract, supplying equipment to assist the company in expanding its milk powder production.</p><p>A search for alternative market mechanisms appears to be under way, according to reports on the <i>Agrimoney.com</i> site. It was reported that at the beginning of 2014, SMPs traded through the GlobalDairyTrade auction suffered their “biggest fall… in eight months”, when both traded values and volumes fell. This was attributed in part to efforts by buyers to diversify their sources of supply and in part to low volumes available from New Zealand.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘Dairy prices make soft start to 2014 as SMP drops’, 7 January 2014</p><p>
<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/dairy-prices-make-soft-start-to-2014-as-smp-drops--6640.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/dairy-prices-make-soft-start-to-2014-as-sm...</a></p><p><i>Dairyreporter.com</i>, ‘Asian milk powder demand drove €120 m Q4 deals: GEA’, 10 January 2014</p><p>
<a href="http://www.dairyreporter.com/Processing-Packaging/Asian-milk-powder-demand-drove-120m-Q4-deals-GEA" target="_self">http://www.dairyreporter.com/Processing-Packaging/Asian-milk-powder-dema...</a></p><p>Radio New Zealand, ‘Arla joins global dairy trade auction’, 3 December 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/rural/229710/arla-joins-global-dairy-trade-auction" target="_self">http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/rural/229710/arla-joins-global-dairy-trade...</a></p><p><i>Money.msn.co.nz</i>, ‘Arla Foods signs up to Fonterra auctions’, 15 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://money.msn.co.nz/businessnews/national/8390072/arla-foods-signs-up-to-fonterra-auctions" target="_self">http://money.msn.co.nz/businessnews/national/8390072/arla-foods-signs-up...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>With the abolition of EU milk production quotas, competitive areas for milk production in the EU are likely to greatly increase their production volumes, with global markets taking on increased significance for the most competitive EU dairy companies. However, companies appear to be favouring different approaches to the development of overseas markets. For some companies in some markets, acquisitions are the most favoured approach for expanding sales of milk powders (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Danone-looking-to-expand-in-West-Africa" target="_blank">Danone looking to expand in West Africa</a>’, 19 January 2014); some companies in certain markets favour joint ventures (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Arla-launches-turnkey-milk-powder-packaging-facility-in-Cote-d-Ivoire" target="_blank">Arla launches turnkey milk powder packaging facility in Côte d’Ivoire</a>’, 27 October 2013); and other companies favour establishing wholly owned subsidiaries (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Expanding-Dutch-corporate-involvement-in-local-milk-procurement-in-Nigeria" target="_blank">Expanding Dutch corporate involvement in local milk procurement in Nigeria</a>’, 15 April 2013).</p><p>For more remote markets whose size and complexity are a challenge to the new global orientation of EU dairy companies, an auction site that is more independent of a major global competitor would also appear to be an important complementary means for expanding sales.</p><p>It is unclear what the implications of a major alternative to Fonterra’s GlobalDairyTrade auction would be for ACP dairy sectors. Competition between two auction sites could serve to reduce the cost of SMP purchases by domestic ACP dairy companies seeking raw materials to expand their production of dairy products. What knock-on effects this might have on local milk supply chains will be strongly influenced by the policy frameworks that ACP governments set in place for local dairy sector development – specifically the frameworks established for the use of imported SMPs and other bulk dairy commodities in meeting expanding domestic and regional demand (see <i>Agritrade</i> ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Executive-Brief-Update-2013-Dairy-sector" target="_blank">Executive Brief Update 2013: Dairy sector</a>’, 18 December 2013).</p>
		</div>
		
